WEBVTT

00:00.835 --> 00:01.633
Junior:
<i> Miss queenie,</i>

00:01.769 --> 00:02.468
<i> I had no idea</i>
<i> any of this</i>

00:02.470 --> 00:03.302
<i> Was touching</i>
<i> your territory.</i>

00:03.437 --> 00:04.303
Means the only
business that remains

00:04.305 --> 00:05.571
Is how you plan to
make this right.

00:05.706 --> 00:07.572
Junior:
<i> Let me use the trains</i>
<i> to run numbers for ya.</i>

00:07.641 --> 00:09.641
<i> Pay and part ways.</i>

00:09.643 --> 00:11.143
Rose:
<i> Boys like ours,</i>

00:11.278 --> 00:13.111
They need more help than
we know how to give.

00:13.147 --> 00:15.447
Marlene:
<i> Eli is pulling us off</i>
<i> our regular route.</i>

00:15.483 --> 00:16.981
He seems to think that
we can do just as well

00:17.018 --> 00:18.217
On de bullion street.

00:18.219 --> 00:19.818
<i> None of these folks are</i>
<i> gonna donate to anything</i>

00:19.854 --> 00:21.653
<i> Besides their own vices.</i>

00:22.489 --> 00:23.522
Who let these preachers in?

00:23.524 --> 00:24.923
You all right?

00:25.059 --> 00:26.491
<i> I think you're a diabetic.</i>

00:27.194 --> 00:28.660
Who's this johnson?

00:28.662 --> 00:30.596
Corrine:
<i> Rumour is he's looking</i>
<i> for a dancer to go along.</i>

00:30.731 --> 00:32.130
Lucy:
<i> He chose corrine.</i>

00:32.199 --> 00:34.199
<i> You need to leave</i>
<i> mr. Senior executive.</i>

00:34.201 --> 00:36.000
Franklin:
<i> But I have some friends</i>
<i> from prep school.</i>

00:36.037 --> 00:37.402
They hold a salon
every few weeks.

00:37.404 --> 00:39.538
Zeke:
<i> If I wanted to get the</i>
<i> porters into a union</i>

00:39.540 --> 00:41.139
<i> That purposely</i>
<i> excludes them,</i>

00:41.274 --> 00:42.808
<i> What's the first</i>
<i> thing I should do?</i>

00:42.877 --> 00:44.109
Randolph:
<i> Always go for the head.</i>

00:44.244 --> 00:46.478
You have to go to the
labour board in ottawa.

00:46.547 --> 00:47.946
They're the ones
with the sway

00:48.082 --> 00:49.281
<i> To change things</i>
<i> for everybody.</i>

00:49.416 --> 00:51.416
Junior:
<i> Think if I have to spend</i>
<i> the rest of my life</i>

00:51.419 --> 00:54.419
<i> Bowing and smiling at people</i>
<i> rather spit in my face</i>

00:54.555 --> 00:55.454
<i> Than see me as human,</i>

00:55.456 --> 00:57.756
<i> Then killing me</i>
<i> would be a kindness.</i>

00:57.891 --> 00:59.024
(dramatic music swells)

00:59.026 --> 01:05.697
(dreamy music)

01:05.699 --> 01:07.832
(muffled banging)

01:07.868 --> 01:09.768
Tuffy:
(muffled)<i> zeke?</i>

01:09.903 --> 01:11.036
(door knocks)

01:11.038 --> 01:12.304
Tuffy:
<i> Zeke!</i>

01:13.574 --> 01:16.007
Didn't no one teach
you to knock?

01:16.043 --> 01:17.509
I-I did.

01:17.912 --> 01:19.177
Twice.

01:20.314 --> 01:21.713
I was wondering if you
had a spare polish brush?

01:21.715 --> 01:24.082
Fellas in my room say it
get more tips than a rag.

01:24.085 --> 01:25.717
Best shine takes both.

01:28.089 --> 01:29.187
You know tuffy,

01:29.322 --> 01:30.589
<i> One of these days</i>

01:30.591 --> 01:31.723
You have to spend
your own money

01:31.759 --> 01:32.925
On your own supplies.

01:33.060 --> 01:34.526
One of these days I'll have
to do better than break even

01:34.595 --> 01:35.794
So I can.

01:35.796 --> 01:37.329
Well that's the nail
on the head ain't it?

01:37.464 --> 01:41.399
(upbeat music)

01:41.435 --> 01:43.067
I talked to the
head of the union,

01:43.104 --> 01:45.270
Now they plan to get
us into the cbre.

01:45.272 --> 01:47.005
You're dreamin' zeke.
-Hey zeke.

01:47.141 --> 01:49.942
No way those white boys
let us in their union.

01:49.944 --> 01:51.677
Well it ain't about
what they want,

01:51.812 --> 01:53.679
It's about what
they need,

01:53.814 --> 01:55.547
And what they
need is numbers.

01:55.549 --> 01:57.549
See, now if I could
get enough names

01:57.585 --> 01:58.683
And dudes from
the porters,

01:58.752 --> 01:59.751
Then I can show
the labour board

01:59.753 --> 02:01.019
That we ready
to be union men.

02:01.088 --> 02:04.689
Okay, okay, but what
good's a union to me?

02:04.758 --> 02:06.925
Well the same thing
it is to them.

02:06.927 --> 02:07.859
Higher wages,

02:07.928 --> 02:08.994
Breaks on
back-to-back runs,

02:09.129 --> 02:11.597
And paid time and a
half on holidays.

02:11.599 --> 02:14.166
Now if every man on
that train is union,

02:14.301 --> 02:15.767
Well the company
can't move down

02:15.769 --> 02:17.169
One inch of
track un-

02:18.105 --> 02:19.505
Tuffy:
<i> Track of what?</i>

02:22.109 --> 02:23.375
<i> Unless what?</i>

02:26.647 --> 02:28.046
Zeke, you all right?

02:28.649 --> 02:29.581
Yeah.

02:29.617 --> 02:30.782
What's wrong?

02:30.784 --> 02:31.783
Oh, you go on
ahead without me.

02:31.819 --> 02:32.718
Come on, man,
we're going-

02:32.853 --> 02:34.386
Go on, tuffy.

02:34.521 --> 02:39.057
(suspenseful dramatic music)

02:39.193 --> 02:49.801
♪

02:49.837 --> 02:54.940
(rhythmic drum music)

02:57.378 --> 03:00.012
(soft piano music)

03:05.819 --> 03:07.553
Marlene:
<i> Shouldn't you be</i>
<i> getting a move on?</i>

03:09.423 --> 03:10.556
(junior sighs)

03:11.659 --> 03:12.824
You know I'm cooking
up something special

03:12.826 --> 03:13.958
For you tonight,
mrs. Massey.

03:13.994 --> 03:15.627
Promises promises.

03:15.663 --> 03:17.128
Mhm.

03:19.700 --> 03:22.300
Rose asked if you would put
that in the post for her boy.

03:23.837 --> 03:25.571
The address is
on the pamphlet.

03:25.706 --> 03:26.905
She made one
for us too,

03:27.040 --> 03:29.641
So don't go pinching
your way through his.

03:29.677 --> 03:31.309
Black cake?

03:43.390 --> 03:44.322
You ever feel like
a place like this

03:44.391 --> 03:45.791
Could be good for teddy?

03:45.926 --> 03:47.358
<i> I'm not sending my</i>
<i> son to an asylum.</i>

03:47.394 --> 03:48.426
If it helps our boy

03:48.428 --> 03:49.394
Who cares what
they call it?

03:49.396 --> 03:51.396
Marlene:
<i> He's just a baby, junior.</i>

03:51.398 --> 03:53.065
And then one day,

03:53.067 --> 03:54.532
Sooner than we want,

03:56.837 --> 03:58.469
<i> He's gonna be</i>
<i> all grown up.</i>

03:59.573 --> 04:01.273
<i> When that boy steps</i>
<i> foot out on st. Antoine</i>

04:01.342 --> 04:03.242
<i> They ain't gonna see</i>
<i> a baby, marlene.</i>

04:03.377 --> 04:05.977
They gon' see a nigger not
playing by the rules.

04:06.847 --> 04:08.146
And then what?

04:10.684 --> 04:12.284
You'll put that
in the post?

04:16.089 --> 04:17.489
Sure.

04:18.091 --> 04:23.895
(gentle music)

04:23.897 --> 04:26.864
♪

04:26.900 --> 04:28.567
(door creaks)

04:28.569 --> 04:34.573
(gentle music)

04:34.575 --> 04:40.579
♪

04:40.581 --> 04:41.780
You all right?

04:41.849 --> 04:43.848
Eli:
<i> I know you have your</i>
<i> routes to attend to,</i>

04:43.917 --> 04:45.050
<i> So I won't</i>
<i> keep you long.</i>

04:45.119 --> 04:47.585
<i> I wanna say what</i>
<i> an honour it is</i>

04:47.621 --> 04:50.188
<i> To be representing the</i>
<i> good people of st. Antoine</i>

04:50.324 --> 04:51.589
<i> At our upcoming convention.</i>

04:52.459 --> 04:55.327
(audience claps)

04:56.596 --> 04:58.063
We may be the
smallest chapter

04:58.065 --> 04:59.398
In attendance,

04:59.400 --> 05:01.133
But with a more
concerted effort,

05:01.268 --> 05:02.667
I don't see a
reason in the world

05:02.736 --> 05:03.668
We couldn't get

05:03.737 --> 05:04.702
Brother garvey's
notice.

05:04.738 --> 05:06.871
Ah, what kind
of effort?

05:06.907 --> 05:10.075
Eli:
<i> Well, it's less effort and</i>
<i> more efficiency, sister.</i>

05:10.077 --> 05:11.209
For example,

05:11.245 --> 05:12.877
Minimal socializing

05:12.913 --> 05:15.247
Would increase the
amount of visitations,

05:15.249 --> 05:17.215
<i> Thereby creating an</i>
<i> overall increase</i>

05:17.251 --> 05:19.550
<i> In donations</i>
<i> and membership.</i>

05:21.488 --> 05:23.955
Given that you've
had so much success

05:23.957 --> 05:25.423
At your
earlier posting,

05:25.459 --> 05:27.025
Perhaps brother eli,

05:27.160 --> 05:28.426
You would be good
enough to accompany

05:28.462 --> 05:30.562
Sister gwen and I
on our route today.

05:30.631 --> 05:33.931
Help us to identify any
areas of inefficiency.

05:35.001 --> 05:36.968
Well, I'm, ah-
(chuckles)

05:36.970 --> 05:39.237
Sure you good ladies
wouldn't want me under foot.

05:39.306 --> 05:41.606
Marlene:
<i> Oh, you would be</i>
<i> no such thing.</i>

05:41.642 --> 05:43.709
And what a testament it
would be to brother garvey,

05:43.844 --> 05:46.712
To know that he has men
who lead by example.

05:49.650 --> 05:51.783
Well, it would
be my pleasure.

05:51.819 --> 05:54.786
(audience claps)

05:57.057 --> 05:59.358
(train horn whistling)

05:59.493 --> 06:05.464
(upbeat rhythmic music)

06:05.466 --> 06:12.404
♪

06:12.539 --> 06:14.005
You got a little
something on your face.

06:14.007 --> 06:15.240
Fuck you, massey.

06:15.309 --> 06:16.441
(junior laughs)

06:16.477 --> 06:17.976
Don't be like that!

06:17.978 --> 06:20.545
(soft dramatic music)

06:20.680 --> 06:22.214
Zeke:
<i> Looks good on you.</i>

06:22.983 --> 06:27.619
(upbeat rhythmic music)

06:27.688 --> 06:29.153
Old bread and cold soup.

06:29.189 --> 06:30.154
I'm tellin' you,

06:30.190 --> 06:31.289
Every dog has it's day,

06:31.358 --> 06:33.291
And one day that
dog will get bite.

06:34.361 --> 06:35.827
(in patois) serious
bite is what de man get.

06:36.864 --> 06:38.830
Think the fellas would
be behind that?

06:40.534 --> 06:42.801
I mean, them white workers'
food comes fresh and free.

06:42.870 --> 06:45.637
<i> We-we pay out of pocket</i>
<i> for-for this right here.</i>

06:47.040 --> 06:48.640
If we got into the
union, junior-

06:48.709 --> 06:50.174
We have to talk about
this shit right now?

06:50.210 --> 06:52.778
I ain't asking you to stand
on a soapbox, junior.

06:54.148 --> 06:56.915
I-I just need a few porters
who ain't so set against it.

06:56.984 --> 07:00.519
And I need to go to that labour
board with an army by my side.

07:00.521 --> 07:02.587
Well, feel free to take the milk
but I'm gonna take the cream.

07:02.722 --> 07:05.990
Oh, so you think you got
claim to a top crew?

07:06.026 --> 07:07.825
You goddamn right.

07:07.861 --> 07:09.160
And I gotta settle this
situation with queenie

07:09.296 --> 07:10.862
<i> To get this lottery</i>
<i> up and running.</i>

07:10.864 --> 07:12.264
I need 'em just
as bad as you

07:12.399 --> 07:13.664
But I ain't gonna wait
for you to get 'em-

07:13.700 --> 07:15.300
Nigger, you gonna
have to wait.

07:15.369 --> 07:16.667
Really?

07:18.738 --> 07:19.938
(junior chuckles)

07:20.874 --> 07:21.806
You know what?

07:21.875 --> 07:23.341
What?

07:25.412 --> 07:27.279
May the best man win, zeke.

07:27.414 --> 07:28.280
I will.

07:28.415 --> 07:32.050
(upbeat rhythmic music)

07:32.052 --> 07:33.251
Now I'm telling you,

07:33.253 --> 07:35.052
It ain't that far fetched.

07:35.088 --> 07:36.888
It's about the details.

07:36.924 --> 07:39.891
Specifically, not
fucking 'em up.

07:39.927 --> 07:42.160
The company exploits
every worker,

07:42.295 --> 07:44.429
Black and white.

07:44.431 --> 07:46.164
If you really want change,
well you got to-

07:46.299 --> 07:48.099
Keep your mouth shut.

07:48.101 --> 07:50.435
You get questioned,
you know nothing.

07:50.437 --> 07:51.903
You get stopped,

07:51.939 --> 07:53.438
You know no one.

07:53.440 --> 07:55.106
Especially not me.

07:55.108 --> 07:56.107
I mean,

07:56.143 --> 07:58.175
Don't y'all deserve
to lay your head down

07:58.212 --> 08:01.046
After they have you on
your feet eighteen hours?

08:01.181 --> 08:02.513
Junior:
<i> Here's how it works.</i>

08:02.549 --> 08:04.449
<i> Pick three numbers,</i>
<i> place your bet.</i>

08:05.552 --> 08:06.518
<i> The draw's every</i>
<i> three days.</i>

08:06.653 --> 08:09.053
<i> Cash on bet,</i>
<i> no exceptions.</i>

08:09.089 --> 08:10.522
The runner picks
up once a week,

08:10.591 --> 08:12.324
Bet slips included.

08:12.459 --> 08:16.328
And, uh, last three numbers on
the stock total take the win.

08:17.664 --> 08:20.665
Any man working on my team
gets a piece of the action.

08:21.801 --> 08:23.668
Look, stanley.

08:23.803 --> 08:25.537
I know you joined the
welfare committee

08:25.606 --> 08:27.872
To make things
better for us,

08:27.941 --> 08:30.875
But we both know that
ain't happening.

08:30.944 --> 08:33.345
Ain't it time that we-we-we
tried a different tactic?

08:33.480 --> 08:34.745
Dinger:
<i> Ladies!</i>

08:35.682 --> 08:37.349
Are you serving
tea or having it?

08:39.119 --> 08:40.751
My apologies,
mr. Miller.

08:43.490 --> 08:44.756
Sorry zeke,

08:44.825 --> 08:47.759
But I tried that fight
and almost lost my job.

08:47.828 --> 08:50.094
I try it again,
I might get deported.

08:50.163 --> 08:51.229
Stanley.

08:51.364 --> 08:52.630
Stanley, I hope...

08:55.168 --> 08:57.835
Lady in car 3 gave
me the local rundown.

08:57.837 --> 09:00.839
Belleville's got three hot spots
to keep the locals coming.

09:00.974 --> 09:02.107
A barbershop,

09:02.109 --> 09:03.508
A supply store,

09:03.643 --> 09:04.909
And a diner.

09:06.146 --> 09:07.045
<i> Now the boys gonna keep us</i>
<i> covered while we're gone</i>

09:07.047 --> 09:08.579
But we gotta lock
the location fast.

09:08.615 --> 09:10.515
What happens if we
miss the train?

09:10.650 --> 09:12.249
I catch a bullet.

09:12.986 --> 09:16.321
(train rumbles)

09:16.323 --> 09:17.989
(soft rhythmic jazz music)

09:17.991 --> 09:19.123
Eli:
<i> Whoo!</i>

09:19.159 --> 09:20.925
(eli pants)

09:20.994 --> 09:22.394
Eli:
<i> Ladies, can we slow down?</i>

09:22.529 --> 09:24.128
(dog barks)

09:24.164 --> 09:25.796
Easy! Easy there.

09:25.832 --> 09:30.134
(dog barks)

09:30.170 --> 09:31.603
I know what you're doing

09:31.672 --> 09:33.338
And it's not one bit funny.

09:33.340 --> 09:34.606
If that man wants
to come here

09:34.675 --> 09:36.307
Setting rules
for what we do,

09:36.343 --> 09:37.409
He should know
what that entails.

09:37.544 --> 09:39.411
So this has nothing
to do with vengeance

09:39.546 --> 09:41.680
For him punishing us?

09:41.682 --> 09:43.615
Well, I didn't say that.

09:44.685 --> 09:46.351
(woman shrieks)

09:46.353 --> 09:47.351
I hope it's not
all like this.

09:47.387 --> 09:49.220
Untrained nurses
playing doctor.

09:49.222 --> 09:51.022
We teach nutrition
like we're supposed to.

09:51.058 --> 09:53.458
<i> But sometimes people need help</i>
<i> they can't get anywhere else.</i>

09:53.593 --> 09:54.525
(woman shrieks)

09:54.561 --> 09:55.894
Just relax.

09:55.896 --> 09:57.562
Gwen:
<i> At least marlene comes</i>
<i> from healing people,</i>

09:57.564 --> 09:58.696
Three generations.

09:58.732 --> 10:00.031
Healing hands or not,
if this-

10:00.067 --> 10:01.532
Gwen!

10:04.237 --> 10:06.037
<i> You're about to be a mama.</i>

10:06.073 --> 10:08.640
(woman shrieks)

10:08.775 --> 10:13.244
(men laugh)
(train horn whistles)

10:13.246 --> 10:16.213
(indistinct chattering)

10:18.818 --> 10:21.186
These the people you're
looking to keep company with?

10:21.321 --> 10:22.586
Zeke:
<i> It's bigger than them, junior.</i>

10:22.623 --> 10:23.855
Junior:
<i> No it's not.</i>

10:23.857 --> 10:26.057
I mean, how you gonna sell
these charleys as a solution

10:26.126 --> 10:27.192
When they're the whole
goddamn problem.

10:27.327 --> 10:28.860
Not very well, apparently.

10:30.330 --> 10:33.131
Guessing you got your
cream crew together?

10:33.133 --> 10:35.066
It's not complicated, zeke.

10:35.135 --> 10:37.802
What I offer these boys
is not "one day maybe",

10:37.804 --> 10:39.404
It is in their
hands right now.

10:39.473 --> 10:42.407
Only you gotta risk your
neck with a gangster for it.

10:42.476 --> 10:44.242
Junior:
<i> Calculated risk</i>
<i> you can measure.</i>

10:45.245 --> 10:46.878
But this union shit
you're talkin',

10:47.814 --> 10:49.214
Now that's danger.

10:51.485 --> 10:53.284
Look, you want my help
getting the boys in the room,

10:53.320 --> 10:55.687
I'll get 'em in the room.

10:55.689 --> 10:57.088
The rest is on you.

10:58.491 --> 11:03.094
(steven choking)

11:03.130 --> 11:05.030
What the hell
happened to him?

11:06.099 --> 11:07.565
(in patois) look like
the dog get bite.

11:07.634 --> 11:13.437
(playful drum music)

11:14.508 --> 11:15.907
Marlene:
<i> Gwen will stay</i>
<i> and finish up.</i>

11:17.044 --> 11:18.910
So much to do and so
little time, brother eli,

11:18.979 --> 11:20.344
Keep up.

11:22.816 --> 11:25.116
Can we kindly cut the shit,
sister massey?

11:26.486 --> 11:28.853
I had no more say
in my appointment

11:28.855 --> 11:31.189
Than you did the
appointed man,

11:31.191 --> 11:33.258
But don't you think
it's time we,

11:33.393 --> 11:34.859
We stopped testing
each other?

11:34.861 --> 11:37.862
<i> The u.N.I.A is quite clear</i>
<i> on the role of its nurses.</i>

11:37.864 --> 11:39.997
Educate our people
on good health.

11:40.033 --> 11:41.032
Enlighten them to-

11:41.034 --> 11:43.000
I didn't start out
delivering babies

11:43.036 --> 11:44.502
And tending to
broken bones.

11:45.672 --> 11:48.273
But when you're faced
with that kind of need,

11:48.408 --> 11:49.941
How are you supposed to
turn your back on that?

11:50.076 --> 11:52.676
<i> What does this have</i>
<i> to do with the u.N.I.A?</i>

11:52.713 --> 11:54.678
Brother garvey says that
we are supposed to create

11:54.715 --> 11:56.614
Our own opportunities.

11:56.650 --> 11:59.718
<i> Why should our people walk</i>
<i> miles to a city hospital</i>

11:59.853 --> 12:02.787
That shuts the door in their
face whenever the mood strikes?

12:03.490 --> 12:04.989
<i> We need our own clinics.</i>

12:06.026 --> 12:07.425
If you would just
look at my plans-

12:07.560 --> 12:09.961
You know there's a reason
why you're in the uniform

12:10.030 --> 12:11.763
And I'm in the suit!

12:11.898 --> 12:14.298
There are roles to
be obeyed marlene,

12:14.367 --> 12:16.834
